<paragraph blockId="9.[809,1422,288,971]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">
<emphasis box="[810,1249,500,524]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[810,967,500,524]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Identification.</emphasis>
This is the only species of
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1865" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1865" class="Mammalia" family="Mephitidae" genus="Spilogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1256,1421,500,524]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" reason="1">
<emphasis box="[1256,1355,500,524]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Spilogale</emphasis>
Gray,
</emphasis>
1865
</taxonomicName>
recorded in 
<collectingRegion box="[996,1116,533,557]" country="Mexico" name="Chihuahua" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Chihuahua</collectingRegion>
. It is black dorsally with extensive white markings and a dorsal pair of white stripes beginning at the ears (
<bibRefCitation author="Van Gelder RG" box="[1045,1227,601,625]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" pagination="229 - 392" refId="ref11398" refString="Van Gelder RG (1959) A taxonomic revision of the spotted skunks (genus Spilogale). Bulletin American Museum of Natural History 117: 229 - 392." type="journal article" year="1959">Van Gelder 1959</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Verts BJ &amp; Carraway LN &amp; Kinlaw A" box="[1237,1411,601,625]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref11428" refString="Verts BJ, Carraway LN, Kinlaw A (2001) Spilogale gracilis. Mammalian Species 674: 1 - 10. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 0.674.1" type="journal article" year="2001">Verts et al. 2001</bibRefCitation>
). It is smaller than the two other skunk genera in 
<collectingRegion box="[1296,1416,634,658]" country="Mexico" name="Chihuahua" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Chihuahua</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="678" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[809,1422,288,971]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[810,958,673,697]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Distribution.</emphasis>
Southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[1132,1217,673,697]" name="Canada" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Canada</collectingCountry>
, western 
<collectingCountry box="[1333,1385,673,697]" name="United States of America" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">USA</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[810,892,707,731]" name="Mexico" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[905,1072,707,731]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Baja California</collectingRegion>
through northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1271,1353,707,731]" name="Mexico" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Mexico</collectingCountry>
to the TMVB; 
<bibRefCitation author="Verts BJ &amp; Carraway LN &amp; Kinlaw A" box="[903,1083,740,765]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref11428" refString="Verts BJ, Carraway LN, Kinlaw A (2001) Spilogale gracilis. Mammalian Species 674: 1 - 10. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 0.674.1" type="journal article" year="2001">Verts et al. 2001</bibRefCitation>
). Recorded habitats in 
<collectingRegion country="Mexico" name="Chihuahua" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Chihuahua</collectingRegion>
are quebradas, sierras and arid lands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="678" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[809,1422,288,971]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[810,921,813,837]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Remarks.</emphasis>
This is the smallest of the skunks in 
<collectingRegion country="Mexico" name="Chihuahua" pageId="9" pageNumber="678">Chihuahua</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez-Gonzalez C &amp; Garcia-Mendoza D" box="[863,1342,846,871]" pageId="9" pageNumber="678" pagination="1122 - 1133" refId="ref10434" refString="Lopez-Gonzalez C, Garcia-Mendoza D (2012) A checklist of the mammals (Mammalia) of Chihuahua, Mexico. Check List 8 (6): 1122 - 1133. https: // doi. org / 10.15560 / 8.6.1122" type="journal article" year="2012">López-González and García-Mendoza 2012</bibRefCitation>
). It has been recorded in three of the four ecological regions of the state; however, in the ranch, it is the skunk with the fewest records.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
